VARIABLE abc


" --------------------------" PRINTLN
" Markdown to HTML Converter" PRINTLN
" in Symbolic FORTH"          PRINTLN
" --------------------------" PRINTLN
" " PRINTLN

( nope ) " yup"

(
In this simple markdown-to-html translator we use ua simple, restricted model
of markdown.

Each markdown block element is a single line of text. The first word of that
line indicates the markdown formatting command. The rest of the line is the
content, or the subject of the formatting command.

One exception is the paragraph -- if the first word doees not correspond to
a formatting command, the default paragraph formatting command is used, and
the first word is joined with the rest of the line as the content.

For example:

# My Title

is an H1 header with the content "My Title"

In-line formatting is accompblished with a secondary process which inspects the
content. This is a byte-by-byte process, in which a particular sequence of
characters triggers a similar formatting context process, with a particular
sequence of characters terminating it.

E.g.

This is a __paragraph__ of "text".

In this case the initial __ triggers the "string" formatting context, ending
with the second __, resulting in the word "paragraph" being displayed within
the "strong" tag, like <strong>paragraph</strong>. The quoted "text" is just
plain text because the double-quote " is not a formatting command.

---------------------------------

To run the formatter you need a javascript runtime installed. I use
QuickJS, thus:

qjs sf.js md-to-html.forth manual/intro.md

---------------------------------

See https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/

)



(

input_file @ file::load VARIABLE contents

contents @ string::length VARIABLE file_len

A[ " File is " file_len @ "  bytes long" ] PRINTLN

)


( here is what we do:
  begin loop
    get the next word
    if the word is recognized
      run it
    if the word is not, assume it is a paragraph
      output the entire line as a paragraph
  end loop
  later we will implement in-line stuff
)


